type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The set <fr:tex>\mathbb {R}</fr:tex> of real numbers is <fr:link
href="jms-00MH.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MH">uncountable</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3875</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:addr>#375</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-375.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00NJ</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>Of course, as <fr:tex>\mathbb {R}</fr:tex> is non-empty, it is enough to show that it is not <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable</fr:link>. We know that <fr:tex>\mathbb {R} \cong   { \mathopen {} \left  [ 0,1 \right  ] \mathclose {}} \cong   { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathbb {N} \to { \mathopen {} \left  [ 2 \right  ] \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}} \cong   \mathcal {P} { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathbb {N} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, and and it follows from <fr:ref
addr="jms-00NF"
href="jms-00NF.xml"
taxon="Theorem"></fr:ref> that the latter is not <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>4783</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00NB</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00NB.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Disjoint unions of enumerable sets</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>I</fr:tex> be an <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable set</fr:link> and let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="jms-00N9.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00N9">family of sets</fr:link> indexed in <fr:tex>I</fr:tex> such that each <fr:tex>A_i</fr:tex> is <fr:link
