type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable</fr:link>. Then the disjoint union <fr:tex>A =  \coprod _{i \in  I}A_i</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3852</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:addr>#378</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-378.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00NB</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>By assumption, we have an <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumeration</fr:link> <fr:tex>e_I \colon   \mathbb {N} \twoheadrightarrow  I</fr:tex>; as each <fr:tex>A_i</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumerable</fr:link>, we may use the <fr:link
href="jms-00MM.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MM">axiom of choice</fr:link> to assign to each <fr:tex>i \in  I</fr:tex> a specific <fr:tex>e_i \colon   \mathbb {N} \twoheadrightarrow  A_i</fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>h \colon \mathbb {N} \twoheadrightarrow \mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N}</fr:tex> be any <fr:link
href="jms-00ME.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00ME">enumeration</fr:link> of <fr:tex>\mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N}</fr:tex>. Define <fr:tex>k \colon \mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N} \to  A</fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex
display="block">   k { \mathopen {} \left ( m,n \right ) \mathclose {}}  = e_{e_I { \mathopen {} \left ( m \right ) \mathclose {}} } { \mathopen {} \left ( n \right ) \mathclose {}}   </fr:tex>

 <fr:p>The function <fr:tex>k \colon \mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N} \to  A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00M8.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00M8">surjective</fr:link>: fixing <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex>, we must find <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( m,n \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>k { \mathopen {} \left ( m,n \right ) \mathclose {}} =a</fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex>i= \pi _A { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>; because <fr:tex>e_I</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00M8.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00M8">surjective</fr:link>, we may find <fr:tex>m \in   \mathbb {N}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>e_I { \mathopen {} \left ( m \right ) \mathclose {}} = \pi _A { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, and because <fr:tex>e_{ \pi _A { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}} }</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00M8.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00M8">surjective</fr:link>, we may find <fr:tex>n \in   \mathbb {N}</fr:tex> such that <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex>e_{ \pi _A { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}} } { \mathopen {} \left ( n \right ) \mathclose {}}  = a</fr:tex>.</html:span> Therefore, we have <fr:tex>k { \mathopen {} \left ( m,n \right ) \mathclose {}}  = e_{e_I { \mathopen {} \left ( m \right ) \mathclose {}} } { \mathopen {} \left ( n \right ) \mathclose {}}  = e_{ \pi _A { \mathopen {} \left ( a \right ) \mathclose {}} } { \mathopen {} \left ( n \right ) \mathclose {}} =a</fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
